{
  "doc_id": "1225",
  "text": "However, although validated as a root-specific gene in Eucalyptus, the cloned EgHAK5 promoter fragment was unable to drive root-specific expression in transgenic tobacco plants. In this regard, despite the presence d and e Root samples with GUS staining in the vascular tissues. f Cross-section of a stained root showing GUS signal in the phloem cells (arrow). g GUS staining in the vasculature of the hypocotyl of a 25 day-old seedling of two cis-elements (TAC ATG T and ATA AAA T) known to be functionally relevant for proper expression in roots [CITATION_1] , EgHAK5 promoter-derived GUS staining, although restricted to vascular tissues, was histochemically detected in the entire seedling. Intriguingly, the GW-amplified EgHAK5 promoter fragment shares common regulatory elements with AtHAK5, which is reported to be expressed in roots [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In a previous study, the activity of a longer version of the AtHAK5 promoter (2.0 kb from the ATG) was shown to be more pronounced in the epidermis of main and lateral roots and less intense in the vasculature [CITATION_4] ). However, after K + resupply, GUS staining was detected only in the root vasculature. On the other hand, a shorter version of the AtHAK5 promoter (1.25 kb from the ATG) with almost the same size of the tested EgHAK5 promoter (1.3 kb) was able to drive GUS expression in the elongating region of primary and lateral roots only under K + deprivation [CITATION_5] . Likewise, the promoter of a rice HAK5 transporter (OsHAK5) directed preferential reporter expression in the root and root-shoot junction under K + deprivation [CITATION_6] . Although requiring further investigation, the inability of the cloned EgHAK5 promoter to confer root-specific expression could be attributed to the lack of additional tissue-specific regulatory elements or to the absence in tobacco of a Eucalyptus-specific transacting factor. Emphasizing the complex regulatory network involved in the control of HAK gene expression, [CITATION_7] reported that, apart from RAP2.11 and ARF2, at least four additional transcription factors can bind to the AtHAK5 promoter and activate its expression under K + starvation. Our results also indicate that the activity of the EgHAK5 promoter is induced by K + starvation, a feature that is in line with the known low K + -inducibility of HAK5 genes from other plant species [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] ). The AtHAK5 promoter, for example, triggers an induction of GUS expression under low K + supply [CITATION_11] ). Compared to AtHAK5 that is up-regulated after 48 h of K + of starvation [CITATION_12] ), here we show that a 24 h K + -deprivation period was sufficient to activate the EgHAK5 promoter, thus pointing to a rapid transcriptional response. Previous studies have shown that AtHAK5 is positively and negatively regulated by the transcription factors RAP2.11 and ARF2, respectively [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] . The mechanistic reason for the fine-tuned regulation of AtHAK5 has been associated with energy saving under K + -sufficient conditions [CITATION_15] . In this respect, the presence of RAP2.11 and ARF2 binding sites within the EgHAK5 promoter suggests that its transcription could be modulated by both regulatory factors through an ethylene and/ or auxin signaling pathways.",
